{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016pL3ewFnwHPeKnSoM2iLMG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see - there are NO secrets `es-transport-ca1` or `es-transport-ca2`. Only the `es-transport-ca-bundle` configmap was created by the precondition.\n\nThe `es_env_ready` probe returned 7 (so the environment was already set up with running pods). Let me understand the probe logic better.\n\nLooking at the `es_env_ready` unit:\n```yaml\non_probe_fail: skip\nprobe:\n  - command: \"kubectl -n elasticsearch get pods 2>/dev/null | grep -c Running\"\n    timeout_sec: 10\n```\n\nThe probe counts running pods. If it returns 0 (no running pods), it exits with code 1 (grep exits with 1 when no match). So when there are no pods running, the probe FAILS → `on_probe_fail: skip` → skip the unit (don't apply the fresh cluster).\n\nBut that's backwards from what we want! If no pods are running, we DO want to apply (set up the fresh cluster). I think I have the `on_probe_fail` semantics backwards — let me reconsider what happens when the probe fails and we skip the apply.\n\nActually, maybe the logic is: if the probe fails (environment not ready), we should run apply to set it up, not skip it. So `on_probe_fail: skip` would mean we're skipping the apply when we actually need it. I need to check the source code to understand the exact behavior.\n```","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":384,"cache_read_input_tokens":49998,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":384},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"30edf2ef-bdf1-46e1-a3d5-a7082b294e9f","uuid":"f68e31c3-6462-4934-b95d-11a063f3e7f1","request_id":"req_011CccGahZ485yq5UBwmPW8U"}
