{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MWhxKxuhiGmLugVMLpaLMM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the precondition logic:\n\n1. **probe_ok = True** → target state already present → SKIP apply (unit is done, no changes needed)\n2. **probe_ok = False** with `on_probe_fail = \"error\"` → fatal failure\n3. **probe_ok = False** with `on_probe_fail = \"skip\"` → fall through to apply\n\nSo `on_probe_fail: skip` doesn't mean \"skip when probe fails\". It's the type of skip-gate behavior:\n- \"skip\" = skip-gate: probe failing means \"not present yet\", so fall through to apply\n- \"error\" = error-gate: probe failing after retries is fatal\n\nAnd probe passing means \"already present, no need to apply\" → skip the apply.\n\nFor the `es_env_ready` precondition in `transport-additional-ca-trust`, the probe runs a kubectl command to count running pods in the elasticsearch namespace, which returned 7 with exit code 0.\n\nSince the probe passed, that means the target state is already present, so the apply is skipped entirely. The fresh-build was never executed because the cluster was already running.\n\nNow I'm trying to identify what the actual degradation is that the prompt is describing by looking at the resource directory for this case.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1318,"cache_read_input_tokens":51369,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1318},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"30edf2ef-bdf1-46e1-a3d5-a7082b294e9f","uuid":"f9ed7116-3e1a-4426-adef-31eab98980dc","request_id":"req_011CccGc71ihuD3FDCN1Y9bA"}
